This is not achievable in one week with one engineer, and claiming otherwise would be dishonest. Here is why, and what is realistic.

Formal verification of a distributed consensus protocol (e.g., Raft or Paxos) is a multi-person-year effort. The IronFleet project (Microsoft Research) took a team of PhDs roughly two years to produce a verified Paxos implementation in Dafny. A Lean 4 port of comparable scope with zero axioms and zero Mathlib would be harder, not easier, because you must build all supporting mathematical infrastructure from scratch.

The blocking issues: (1) Modeling asynchronous message-passing networks with crashes requires a substantial verified I/O monad or a shim layer; building that alone takes weeks. (2) The safety proof for even single-decree Paxos requires ~50–100 non-trivial lemmas about quorum intersection, ballot ordering, and invariant preservation under all interleavings. (3) Liveness requires fairness assumptions that are notoriously hard to formalize without importing topology or measure theory, both of which live in Mathlib. (4) "Production-ready" implies an executable extraction story; Lean 4 code generation is immature for systems use. (5) No axioms is a very strong constraint — classical logic (propDecidable, funext, propext) is used implicitly throughout any realistic protocol proof and would need careful management or elimination.

A realistic one-week deliverable for one senior Lean 4 engineer: a mechanized safety proof of single-decree Paxos in a pure message-passing model, with network state as an inductive type, no liveness, no extraction, using only core Lean 4 plus a small hand-rolled finite-set library. That is still aggressive but plausible. Call it a verified specification, not a production protocol. Liveness, fault-tolerant execution, and the no-Mathlib constraint on liveness all push the honest timeline to six to twelve months minimum.
